Narrowed based on some statistical history of both home teams winning, vegas spread so thin, and the AFC game being more heavily weighted towards KC to win. Interestingly enough, both home teams have not won as much. And given this game will not have a heavily favored home-field advantage (both teams from CA), this should not weigh as much as another game at Arrowhead against a wildcard opponent simply lacking the horses to stay with KC (last part is opinion).

The Rams have too many star players for the 49ers, and those players are all healthy at the right time. The Niners quarterback, Jimmy Garrapolo, is not a great quarterback, and then Niners have gone as far as they can go without a first rate quarterback.
Updated based on weekend games. I am still favoring the Rams in line with last forecast.
Updating to reflect losses by Green Bay and Tampa (and setting my forecast in accordance with the win-loss record of the remaining two teams).

The NFC championship is now all CA teams. This one could be closer to a coin flip. Both teams needed some luck to win their last games. Overall the Rams have a better and more consistent and successful record, but only slightly. 49ers had a huge comeback to win in overtime, while the Rams grabbed a win in the last few seconds with a field goal.
49ers with the upset.

The following games for NFC are 49ers vs Packers and Rams vs Buccaneers. Packers and Buccaneers are clear favorites, and although Aaron Rodgers is currently playing very well, it is hard to reason past Tom Brady's leadership.

11 Jan = Green Bay Packers, Tampa Bay Buccaneers, LA Rams, San Fransisco 49ers, Dallas Cowboys; but after the week of performance I am revising my 18 Jan forecast to Green Bay Packers, Tampa Bay Buccaneers, LA Rams, Dallas Cowboys, Arizona Cardinals. Essentially, Green Bay still looks stronger, and the 49ers come out and the Cardinals are in.
Adjusting again to reflect standings changes since the 15th. This forecast reflects ESPN-reported standings and NFL-reported playoff qualifiers as of January 18.

Base rate is the W-L record for the 21-22 season, factoring in the home/away records and injuries. Other factors could include the location/weather of where the championship game will be played (but not much - these are professionals).
With the win of Tampa Bay against the Eagles it further justifies that Tampa Bay is a force to be reckoned with and stands a more that 50% chance of winning it all.
Late to the game here, but Packers home field advantage and success in Lambeau are difficult to ignore, especially as weather worsens and a TB matchup there remains a high probability.
I'm left wondering if forecasters really believe that the Eagles and 49ers have a combined 0% chance to win the NFC Championship.

Adjusting Tampa Bay up a bit to be on par with Green Bay, Dallas to be on par with LA, and New Orleans down (I ranked it too high before by mistake. maybe?) based on ESPN NFC rankings as of January 15.

I choose the Buccaneers because first they won last year and where that isn’t a definitive data point there are enough data points to suggest that they may be riding high. Also Tom Brady doesn’t go down easily. Having said all of that I will review this forecast and amend very soon.

Eight teams have repeated Super Bowl victories, so it’s in frequent, but not rare. Tom Brady has played in nine of the last 19 and won seven of them. Aaron Rodgers has won three MVP awards and will likely win this years.

As much as I hate to say it, Tom Brady has the best chance to lead his team to an NFC championship based on past playoff experience and success. Green Bay is the second most likely with Aaron Rogers experience and recent win streak, but team dynamics risk dysfunction going into the playoffs. The Chargers also have a strong winning streak from December.

Reflecting current records, as well as the Cowboys and Rams impressive NFC history, Green Bay in the hunt the last 5-6 years consistently, and Tom Brady #goat. Random biases, Aaron Rogers COVID toe mutant strength.
